<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,546,1975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,654,679]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[331,540,654,679]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="585" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fiorentini" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[331,540,654,679]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Haliplus fiorentini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[549,615,654,679]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[549,615,654,679]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be distinguished from other neotropical species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1258,1355,654,678]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="585" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1258,1355,654,678]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Haliplus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characteristics: elytra yellow-brown with extensive and well-defined maculation consisting of black patches (
<figureCitation box="[473,540,726,751]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1973,1996]" captionTargetBox="[179,1353,230,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[167,1420,187,1960]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. HabituS of Haliplus SpecieS (Coleoptera, Haliplidae) holotye male. H. fiorentini sp. n.: 1) dorSal view; 2) ventral view; H. regili sp. n.: 3) dorSal view; 4) ventral view. ScaleS: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827872/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); prosternal process parallel, straight, wider and short, about 1.15 times longer than wide at base (
<figureCitation box="[361,429,762,787]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1898,1921]" captionTargetBox="[268,1327,263,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[198,1389,193,1877]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 12. Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. (Coleoptera, Haliplidae), male holotype: 5) antenna; 6) punctureS near elytral baSe and Suture; 7) hind tibia in dorSal view; 8) proSternal and metaventral proceSS; 9) proSternal proceSS in lateral view; 10) left paramere; 11) median lobe; 12) right paramere. ScaleS: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827874/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); metaventral process with a long diverging groove on each side and not impressed in the middle (
<figureCitation box="[245,315,798,823]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1973,1996]" captionTargetBox="[179,1353,230,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[167,1420,187,1960]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. HabituS of Haliplus SpecieS (Coleoptera, Haliplidae) holotye male. H. fiorentini sp. n.: 1) dorSal view; 2) ventral view; H. regili sp. n.: 3) dorSal view; 4) ventral view. ScaleS: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827872/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), and the median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view curved, subparallel, gradually narrowed, distally elongate and with rounded apex (
<figureCitation box="[524,606,834,859]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1898,1921]" captionTargetBox="[268,1327,263,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[198,1389,193,1877]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 12. Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. (Coleoptera, Haliplidae), male holotype: 5) antenna; 6) punctureS near elytral baSe and Suture; 7) hind tibia in dorSal view; 8) proSternal and metaventral proceSS; 9) proSternal proceSS in lateral view; 10) left paramere; 11) median lobe; 12) right paramere. ScaleS: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827874/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="587" pageId="1" pageNumber="585" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,546,1975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,870,895]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[353,442,870,894]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Habitus</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[458,525,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1973,1996]" captionTargetBox="[179,1353,230,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[167,1420,187,1960]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. HabituS of Haliplus SpecieS (Coleoptera, Haliplidae) holotye male. H. fiorentini sp. n.: 1) dorSal view; 2) ventral view; H. regili sp. n.: 3) dorSal view; 4) ventral view. ScaleS: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827872/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Body oval, tapering backwards, widest just behind the shoulders, with narrow pronotum and shoulders slightly pronounced.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,546,1975]" box="[199,1437,942,967]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis box="[199,361,943,966]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Measurements</emphasis>
(n = 1). TL: 4.0 mm; MW: 
<quantity box="[668,770,943,967]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.37" pageId="1" pageNumber="585" unit="mm" value="2.37">2.37 mm</quantity>
; PL: 
<quantity box="[827,930,942,967]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.4" pageId="1" pageNumber="585" unit="mm" value="0.64">0.64 mm</quantity>
; PW: 
<quantity box="[996,1098,943,967]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.39" pageId="1" pageNumber="585" unit="mm" value="1.39">1.39 mm</quantity>
; DE: 
<quantity box="[1160,1263,942,967]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="585" unit="mm" value="0.26">0.26 mm</quantity>
; EW: 
<quantity box="[1330,1433,943,967]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="585" unit="mm" value="0.3">0.30 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,546,1975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis box="[199,267,979,1003]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Head.</emphasis>
Yellow-brown, vague darkening near antennae and between eyes; finely punctured, not punctured in area between eyes; narrower than pronotum, widest across eyes; width between eyes 0.8 × width of one eye. Antennae yellow; placed anterior to eyes; with 11 antennomeres, 1st and 2nd short and broad, 3–11 long, 11th the largest (
<figureCitation box="[243,313,1086,1111]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1898,1921]" captionTargetBox="[268,1327,263,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[198,1389,193,1877]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 12. Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. (Coleoptera, Haliplidae), male holotype: 5) antenna; 6) punctureS near elytral baSe and Suture; 7) hind tibia in dorSal view; 8) proSternal and metaventral proceSS; 9) proSternal proceSS in lateral view; 10) left paramere; 11) median lobe; 12) right paramere. ScaleS: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827874/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Palpi yellow; maxillary palpi with four palpomeres, the last shorter than the penultimate. Genal lines behind eyes double.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,546,1975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis box="[199,317,1159,1182]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Pronotum.</emphasis>
Yellow-brown, with vague darkened mark in the middle; strongly and densely punctured, anterior punctures small, posterior punctures a little larger; widest at base, narrow towards apex; lateral sides convex, slightly and completely margined; base without plicae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,546,1975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis box="[199,277,1267,1291]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Elytra.</emphasis>
Yellow-brown, with extensive and well-defined maculation consisting of black patches; dark marks along suture to first primary puncture row (
<figureCitation box="[636,702,1302,1327]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1973,1996]" captionTargetBox="[179,1353,230,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[167,1420,187,1960]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. HabituS of Haliplus SpecieS (Coleoptera, Haliplidae) holotye male. H. fiorentini sp. n.: 1) dorSal view; 2) ventral view; H. regili sp. n.: 3) dorSal view; 4) ventral view. ScaleS: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827872/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Primary puncture rows strong, especially in anterior part, about 30 punctures in first row, fifth elytral puncture row basally impressed; secondary puncture rows dense and moderately strong, in anterior part often in two irregular rows, in basal part of second elytral interval in a single row; all punctures darkened (
<figureCitation box="[478,546,1410,1435]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1898,1921]" captionTargetBox="[268,1327,263,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[198,1389,193,1877]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 12. Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. (Coleoptera, Haliplidae), male holotype: 5) antenna; 6) punctureS near elytral baSe and Suture; 7) hind tibia in dorSal view; 8) proSternal and metaventral proceSS; 9) proSternal proceSS in lateral view; 10) left paramere; 11) median lobe; 12) right paramere. ScaleS: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827874/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Lateral margin completely bordered; shoulders and apical margin not serrate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,546,1975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis box="[199,343,1446,1470]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Ventral side.</emphasis>
Brown to yellow-brown, lighter towards coxae. Epipleura yellow-brown, with double row of strong punctures in anterior part and single row of weaker punctures in posterior narrowed part, reaching to the end of sixth sternite. Prosternum margined anteriorly, strongly punctured. Prosternal process parallel, straight, wider and short, about 1.15 times longer than wide at base; anterior edge margined, laterally grooved; moderately strongly and densely punctured (
<figureCitation box="[517,596,1590,1615]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1973,1996]" captionTargetBox="[179,1353,230,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[167,1420,187,1960]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. HabituS of Haliplus SpecieS (Coleoptera, Haliplidae) holotye male. H. fiorentini sp. n.: 1) dorSal view; 2) ventral view; H. regili sp. n.: 3) dorSal view; 4) ventral view. ScaleS: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827872/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[607,651,1591,1615]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1898,1921]" captionTargetBox="[268,1327,263,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[198,1389,193,1877]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 12. Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. (Coleoptera, Haliplidae), male holotype: 5) antenna; 6) punctureS near elytral baSe and Suture; 7) hind tibia in dorSal view; 8) proSternal and metaventral proceSS; 9) proSternal proceSS in lateral view; 10) left paramere; 11) median lobe; 12) right paramere. ScaleS: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827874/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">8, 9</figureCitation>
). Metaventral process, on each side, with a long diverging groove and a short groove starting in the lateral groves and continuing towards the middle; moderately punctured, more densely punctured in lateral parts (
<figureCitation box="[543,614,1662,1687]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1973,1996]" captionTargetBox="[179,1353,230,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[167,1420,187,1960]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. HabituS of Haliplus SpecieS (Coleoptera, Haliplidae) holotye male. H. fiorentini sp. n.: 1) dorSal view; 2) ventral view; H. regili sp. n.: 3) dorSal view; 4) ventral view. ScaleS: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827872/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Metacoxal plates reaching to end of fourth sternite; densely punctured. Fifth and sixth sternite densely punctured, more extensively punctured near the apex; last sternite punctured on the entire surface, uniformly (
<figureCitation box="[444,513,1734,1759]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1973,1996]" captionTargetBox="[179,1353,230,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[167,1420,187,1960]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. HabituS of Haliplus SpecieS (Coleoptera, Haliplidae) holotye male. H. fiorentini sp. n.: 1) dorSal view; 2) ventral view; H. regili sp. n.: 3) dorSal view; 4) ventral view. ScaleS: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827872/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,546,1975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis box="[199,259,1771,1794]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Legs.</emphasis>
Yellow-brown. Fore and mid legs: femur basally narrowed, medially enlarged, surface covered with dense, coarse micropunctures; tibia with long hairs on inner margin, apically with two equal spurs; tarsi with 5 tarsomeres, the 5th longest, tarsal claws of equal length. Hind legs: coxal plates enlarged covering trochanter and most of the femoral region; femur broadest at apex; tibia slender with unequal apical spurs, setiferous striole on dorsal face of 1/4 × length, longer apical spur as long as the length of first tarsomere (
<figureCitation box="[1199,1272,1914,1939]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1898,1921]" captionTargetBox="[268,1327,263,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[198,1389,193,1877]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 12. Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. (Coleoptera, Haliplidae), male holotype: 5) antenna; 6) punctureS near elytral baSe and Suture; 7) hind tibia in dorSal view; 8) proSternal and metaventral proceSS; 9) proSternal proceSS in lateral view; 10) left paramere; 11) median lobe; 12) right paramere. ScaleS: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827874/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="585">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); tarsi with 5 tarsomeres, 1st the longest, with a pair of equal claws.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827872/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="586" targetBox="[179,1353,230,1901]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1973,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="586">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,317,1973,1996]" pageId="2" pageNumber="586">FIGURES 1–4.</emphasis>
HabituS of 
<taxonomicName box="[445,532,1974,1995]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[445,532,1974,1995]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="586">Haliplus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SpecieS (
<taxonomicName box="[631,746,1974,1996]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[760,867,1974,1996]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Haliplidae</taxonomicName>
) holotye male. 
<taxonomicName box="[1034,1161,1974,1996]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fiorentini" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1034,1161,1974,1996]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="586">H. fiorentini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1171,1231,1975,1996]" pageId="2" pageNumber="586" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1171,1231,1975,1996]" pageId="2" pageNumber="586">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
: 1) dorSal view; 2) ventral view; 
<taxonomicName box="[290,375,2005,2027]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="regili" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[290,375,2005,2027]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="586">H. regili</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[381,438,2005,2026]" pageId="2" pageNumber="586" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[381,438,2005,2026]" pageId="2" pageNumber="586">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
: 3) dorSal view; 4) ventral view. ScaleS: 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis box="[199,264,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Male.</emphasis>
First three tarsomeres of fore- and midlegs widened and ventrally with a tuft of sucker hairs. Aedeagus: Median lobe in lateral view curved, subparallel, gradually narrowed, distally elongate and with rounded apex; inner margin regularly curved, external margin with a longitudinal groove (
<figureCitation box="[938,1021,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1898,1921]" captionTargetBox="[268,1327,263,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[198,1389,193,1877]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 12. Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. (Coleoptera, Haliplidae), male holotype: 5) antenna; 6) punctureS near elytral baSe and Suture; 7) hind tibia in dorSal view; 8) proSternal and metaventral proceSS; 9) proSternal proceSS in lateral view; 10) left paramere; 11) median lobe; 12) right paramere. ScaleS: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827874/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Left paramere in lateral view short and broad, subtriangular, with basal process narrow, and with apex angular; with two long and some short setae at tip (
<figureCitation box="[197,282,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1898,1921]" captionTargetBox="[268,1327,263,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[198,1389,193,1877]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 12. Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. (Coleoptera, Haliplidae), male holotype: 5) antenna; 6) punctureS near elytral baSe and Suture; 7) hind tibia in dorSal view; 8) proSternal and metaventral proceSS; 9) proSternal proceSS in lateral view; 10) left paramere; 11) median lobe; 12) right paramere. ScaleS: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827874/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Right paramere in lateral view slender, moderately curved, base bilobed, apex pointed, with a short distal appendage; inner margin with a series of large setae in the apical two thirds (
<figureCitation box="[1078,1161,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1898,1921]" captionTargetBox="[268,1327,263,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[198,1389,193,1877]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 12. Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. (Coleoptera, Haliplidae), male holotype: 5) antenna; 6) punctureS near elytral baSe and Suture; 7) hind tibia in dorSal view; 8) proSternal and metaventral proceSS; 9) proSternal proceSS in lateral view; 10) left paramere; 11) median lobe; 12) right paramere. ScaleS: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827874/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="587" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,367,392]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named in honor of Gelson Luiz Fiorentin, a good friend and colleague, in gratitude for all the shared moments during our long friendship and in recognition of his contribution to the knowledge of aquatic insects in 
<collectingCountry box="[351,423,439,464]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="587" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,498,476,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
Northern 
<collectingCountry box="[614,685,476,501]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, currently only known in the state of 
<collectingRegion box="[1108,1204,476,501]" country="Brazil" name="Roraima" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Roraima</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[1221,1305,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1461,1483]" captionTargetBox="[196,1357,190,1424]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[196,1359,190,1424]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 21. Known diStribution of Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. (circle) and H. regili sp. n. (triangle) (Coleoptera, Haliplidae)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827878/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
). Specimen was collected in a shallow pond with macrophytes near the shores (
<figureCitation box="[905,989,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 22 – 23. 22" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1871,1893]" captionText="FIGURE 22 – 23. 22. Habitat of Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. Brazil: Roraima State, Boa ViSta county, pond near the RR- 205 road. 23. Habitat of Haliplus regili sp. n. Brazil: Roraima State, Alto Alegre county, pond near the RR- 205 road" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,471,548,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Taxonomic comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[484,696,548,572]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fiorentini" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[484,696,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Haliplus fiorentini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[709,778,548,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,778,548,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be distinguished from other neotropical species of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,248,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,248,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Haliplus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the combination of characteristics of elytra, prosternal and metaventral processes and the male genitalia shape. The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Chapin, 1930" authorityName="Chapin" authorityYear="1930" box="[677,961,620,645]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassus">
<emphasis box="[677,797,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">H. crassus</emphasis>
Chapin, 1930
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from this species by having a narrow lifted margin of the metaventral process, while in 
<taxonomicName box="[798,917,657,680]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassus">
<emphasis box="[798,917,657,680]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">H. crassus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the lifted margin is broad; by having, on each side of metaventral process, a short groove starting in the lateral grooves and continuing towards the middle, which is absent in 
<taxonomicName box="[292,412,729,752]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassus">
<emphasis box="[292,412,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">H. crassus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and in the male median lobe shape in lateral view, which is narrower, more tapered and curved downward in 
<taxonomicName box="[391,510,765,788]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassus">
<emphasis box="[391,510,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">H. crassus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[525,663,764,788]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fiorentini" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[525,663,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">H. fiorentini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[671,736,764,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[671,736,764,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is also similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Vondel &amp; Spangler, 2008" authorityName="Vondel &amp; Spangler" authorityYear="2008" box="[938,1387,764,789]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis box="[938,1091,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">H. mexicanus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Vondel" box="[1099,1387,764,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" refString="Vondel, B. J. van &amp; Spangler, P. J. (2008) ReviSion of the Haliplidae of the Neotropical Region including Mexico (Coleoptera: Haliplidae). Koleopterologische Rundschau, 78, 69 - 194." type="journal article" year="2008">Vondel &amp; Spangler, 2008</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from the latter species in body shape, being more robust and more tapering apically and with shoulders more pronounced, by the metaventral process is wider, and the two species can be especially well distinguished by the male median lobe shape in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[603,684,871,896]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1898,1921]" captionTargetBox="[268,1327,263,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[198,1389,193,1877]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 12. Haliplus fiorentini sp. n. (Coleoptera, Haliplidae), male holotype: 5) antenna; 6) punctureS near elytral baSe and Suture; 7) hind tibia in dorSal view; 8) proSternal and metaventral proceSS; 9) proSternal proceSS in lateral view; 10) left paramere; 11) median lobe; 12) right paramere. ScaleS: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/827874/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
), which is not parallel in the dorsal edge (parallel in 
<taxonomicName box="[1274,1426,872,896]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis box="[1274,1426,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">H. mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and with the maximum width in the middle (maximum width is near the apex in 
<taxonomicName box="[1053,1205,909,932]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="587" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis box="[1053,1205,909,932]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">H. mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
